{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01SZLN4SkuoJ5YcT8ii8meqz","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Story file created at `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/10-4-model-resolution-module.md`.\n\n**What was done:**\n- Auto-discovered `10-4-model-resolution-module` as the next backlog story from sprint-status.yaml\n- Read the epic definition (epics-multi-framework.md, Story 1.4), architecture (Decision 4: Model Resolution), existing driver code (types.ts, claude-code.ts, factory.ts), agent-resolver.ts, and workflow/agent schemas for full context\n- Created the story file with 10 acceptance criteria, each tagged with `<!-- verification: test-provable -->` (all are pure function/type/build checks)\n- Included tasks/subtasks, dev notes with architecture compliance, current codebase state, input type design rationale, explicit \"What NOT to Do\" guardrails, and references\n\n**Key design decisions in the story:**\n- Function uses structural typing (`{ model?: string | null }`) to avoid coupling to specific config interfaces\n- Empty strings treated as \"not set\" (defensive against YAML parser behavior)\n- Only throws on empty driver defaultModel (the last-resort fallback must be valid)\n- No modifications to existing files beyond barrel export — schema/engine integration deferred to stories 11-1 and 10-5\n\n## Session Issues\n\n**Problems encountered:** None.\n\n**Workarounds applied:** None.\n\n**Risks identified:**\n- The agent config (`ResolvedAgent`) does not yet have a `model` field. The resolver accepts `{ model?: string }` structurally, but the actual wiring of agent-level model into the resolution chain depends on story 11-1 adding the field. Until then, agent-level model will always fall through to driver default in practice.\n\n**Observations:**\n- All 10 ACs are `test-provable` — this is a pure function module with no runtime dependencies. No running app, no Docker stack, no external services needed for verification.\n- The existing `compileSubagentDefinition()` in `agent-resolver.ts` hardcodes `DEFAULT_MODEL`. Story 10-5 (workflow engine driver integration) will need to replace that with a `resolveModel()` call.\n\n## Token Report\n\n- Total tool calls: 18\n- By tool: Read: 8, Glob: 8, Grep: 5, Write: 1, Bash: 0, Edit: 0\n- Largest Bash outputs: N/A (no Bash calls)\n- Files read: 8 unique, 9 total reads (no file read 3+ times)\n- Redundant operations: Two Glob calls for `_bmad-output/**/*10-1*` and `_bmad-output/**/*agentdriver*` overlapped in results (both returned `10-1-agentdriver-interface-types.md`). Minor — needed different search angles."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a9201b83b3d3e06db (use SendMessage with to: 'a9201b83b3d3e06db' to continue this agent)\n<usage>total_tokens: 51512\ntool_uses: 39\nduration_ms: 149594</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2c102368-34ec-49f5-8d34-59f136ae42aa","uuid":"516683f2-e505-48e3-b085-69cacf98576a","timestamp":"2026-04-03T07:20:44.284Z","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Run /create-story for story 10-4-model-resolution-module. The sprint-status.yaml is at _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/sprint-status.yaml. Auto-discover the next backlog story and create it. For each AC, append a verification tier tag using this decision tree:\n\n**Tier Decision Tree (append one `<!-- verification: {tier} -->` tag per AC):**\n- `test-provable` — AC can be verified by building the project and running tests/linters/grep. No running app needed. Examples: 'function X exists', 'type Y is exported', 'test Z passes', 'file has <300 lines'.\n- `runtime-provable` — AC requires running the app locally and checking its behavior (CLI output, HTTP response, process lifecycle). No Docker stack needed. Examples: 'CLI prints usage when invoked with --help', 'server responds 200 on /health', 'process exits 0 on valid input'.\n- `environment-provable` — AC requires a full environment (Docker stack, database, observability, multi-service interaction). Examples: 'logs appear in VictoriaLogs', 'metrics are emitted to VictoriaMetrics', 'container communicates with service X'.\n- `escalate` — AC genuinely cannot be automated (requires physical hardware, paid external service, human visual judgment). This is rare. Examples: 'UI looks correct on mobile', 'payment processes successfully in production'.\n\nDefault to `test-provable` when unsure. Do NOT ask the user any questions — proceed autonomously. Do NOT run git commit. Do NOT run git add. Do NOT modify sprint-status.yaml.\n\nMANDATORY — End your response with a `## Session Issues` section listing:\n- Problems encountered (errors, ambiguities in epic definition, missing context)\n- Workarounds applied (anything you did that felt hacky or suboptimal)\n- Risks identified (ACs that seem untestable, unclear requirements, missing dependencies)\n- Observations (anything surprising or noteworthy about this story)\nIf nothing to report, write `## Session Issues\\n\\nNone.`\n\nMANDATORY — Also end your response with a `## Token Report` section:\n- Total tool calls: N\n- By tool: Bash: X, Read: Y, Edit: Z, Grep: W, Write: V, other: N\n- Largest Bash outputs (top 3 by line count): command (~N lines each)\n- Files read: N unique, M total reads (list any file read 3+ times)\n- Redundant operations: describe any repeated reads, duplicate commands, or wasted calls","agentId":"a9201b83b3d3e06db","agentType":"general-purpose","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Story file created at `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/10-4-model-resolution-module.md`.\n\n**What was done:**\n- Auto-discovered `10-4-model-resolution-module` as the next backlog story from sprint-status.yaml\n- Read the epic definition (epics-multi-framework.md, Story 1.4), architecture (Decision 4: Model Resolution), existing driver code (types.ts, claude-code.ts, factory.ts), agent-resolver.ts, and workflow/agent schemas for full context\n- Created the story file with 10 acceptance criteria, each tagged with `<!-- verification: test-provable -->` (all are pure function/type/build checks)\n- Included tasks/subtasks, dev notes with architecture compliance, current codebase state, input type design rationale, explicit \"What NOT to Do\" guardrails, and references\n\n**Key design decisions in the story:**\n- Function uses structural typing (`{ model?: string | null }`) to avoid coupling to specific config interfaces\n- Empty strings treated as \"not set\" (defensive against YAML parser behavior)\n- Only throws on empty driver defaultModel (the last-resort fallback must be valid)\n- No modifications to existing files beyond barrel export — schema/engine integration deferred to stories 11-1 and 10-5\n\n## Session Issues\n\n**Problems encountered:** None.\n\n**Workarounds applied:** None.\n\n**Risks identified:**\n- The agent config (`ResolvedAgent`) does not yet have a `model` field. The resolver accepts `{ model?: string }` structurally, but the actual wiring of agent-level model into the resolution chain depends on story 11-1 adding the field. Until then, agent-level model will always fall through to driver default in practice.\n\n**Observations:**\n- All 10 ACs are `test-provable` — this is a pure function module with no runtime dependencies. No running app, no Docker stack, no external services needed for verification.\n- The existing `compileSubagentDefinition()` in `agent-resolver.ts` hardcodes `DEFAULT_MODEL`. Story 10-5 (workflow engine driver integration) will need to replace that with a `resolveModel()` call.\n\n## Token Report\n\n- Total tool calls: 18\n- By tool: Read: 8, Glob: 8, Grep: 5, Write: 1, Bash: 0, Edit: 0\n- Largest Bash outputs: N/A (no Bash calls)\n- Files read: 8 unique, 9 total reads (no file read 3+ times)\n- Redundant operations: Two Glob calls for `_bmad-output/**/*10-1*` and `_bmad-output/**/*agentdriver*` overlapped in results (both ret