ask/agent/both levels, whitespace-only driver default throws, model string trimming, agent-with-empty-driver-no-throw.\n\n**Coverage:** 96.73% overall, all 167 files above 80% floor. 164 test files, 4308 tests, zero regressions.\n\n## Session Issues\n\n**Bugs found:**\n- **HIGH**: Driver validation fired unconditionally before cascade resolution, violating architecture Decision 4's nullish-coalescing semantics. A valid task-level model + empty driver.defaultModel would throw instead of returning the task model. Fixed.\n- **MEDIUM**: Whitespace-only model strings (`\"  \"`) passed through as valid model names instead of being treated as \"not set\". Could cause downstream dispatch failures with invisible model names. Fixed.\n- **MEDIUM**: Test on line 129-135 asserted the wrong behavior (expected throw when task has valid model + empty driver default) and documented it as correct with a misleading comment. Fixed.\n\n**Code quality issues found but NOT fixed (LOW):**\n- No Dev Agent Record / File List section in story file — story lacks traceability metadata expected by the review workflow.\n- Story file and new source files are untracked in git (not staged) — this is expected since commit was not requested.\n- The `@throws` JSDoc line still says \"If `driver.defaultModel` is empty or falsy\" without clarifying \"and no task/agent model resolves first\" — minor doc inconsistency.\n\n**Coverage gaps:**\n- None. model-resolver.ts has 100% line/branch/function coverage. All 167 project files above 80% floor.\n\n**Architecture concerns:**\n- The `trim()` behavior means `resolveModel` returns trimmed model strings, while the driver's `defaultModel` is returned untrimmed (line 50 returns `driver.defaultModel` raw). This is a minor asymmetry — if a driver has a defaultModel with trailing whitespace, it would be returned as-is. Acceptable for now since drivers are class instances with hardcoded const strings.\n\n**Items sent back for re-development:**\n- None. All HIGH and ME